solutions.content:
# Intuition
The idea in this problem is to figure out the transitions we can make.

Basically we have the following transitions:

* Put a 2x1 tile ( | ) then we move to the next column.
* Put a 1x2 tile ( _ ) then we must match below and move i+2 column.
* Put an L shape tromino. Then we either close with inverted L or put _ above
* The previous point can also be inverted therefore we multiply the result by 2 of that transition.

The flag `isAdjacentTaken` in the code is for situations where we put an L shape tromino and move to the next column. In this situation, the row beneath (or above because we can invert the tromino) is taken. This is a unique state that we need to account for.

![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/3528a929-a120-43c2-b3cc-3ad326cddd10_1671870454.7892098.png)


# Code
```
class Solution {
    private final int MOD = 1_000_000_007;

    public int numTilings(int n) {
        long[][] dp = new long[n][2];
        for (long[] A : dp) {
            Arrays.fill(A, -1);
        }
        return (int) solve(0, n, false, dp);
    }

    public long solve(int i, int n, boolean isAdjacentTaken, long[][] dp) {
        if (i == n && !isAdjacentTaken) return 1;
        if (i >= n) return 0;
        if (dp[i][isAdjacentTaken ? 0 : 1] != -1) return dp[i][isAdjacentTaken ? 0 : 1];

        long ans = 0;
        if (!isAdjacentTaken) {
            ans += solve(i + 1, n, false, dp); // if we put 2x1 tile
            ans += solve(i + 2, n, false, dp); // 1x2 tiles twice
            ans += 2 * solve(i + 1, n, true, dp); // L shape (and inverted L)
        } else {
            ans += solve(i + 1, n, true, dp); // 1x2 tile and go down
            ans += solve(i + 2, n, false, dp); // L to close
        }
        ans %= MOD;
        return dp[i][isAdjacentTaken ? 0 : 1] = ans;
    }
}

```

