Explaination:
dp[i][1] -> represents number of ways to fill i tiles(length) and ending tile is completely filled
dp[i][0] -> represents number of ways to fill i tiles(length) but ending tile has only one tile filled out of the two.

So we derive the relation:
dp[i][1] = dp[i-1][1] (*fill tiles till i-1 and put a 2x1 tile standing with height as 2*)
\+ dp[i-2][1] (*fill tiles till i-2 and put two 2x1 tiles sitting on top of each other with length as 2*)  
\+ dp[i-1][0] (*fill tiles till i-2 completely but fill only one tile in i-1, and we put a L-shaped tile on the remaining*)

dp[i][0] = (dp[i-2][1]\*2) (*completely fill till i-2 and then we can fill the last two tiles by putting 1 L-shaped tile, so that last tile's one part remains*)
\+ dp[i-1][0] (*fill with last tile remaining a part, and add 2x1 tile in the end horizontally*)


```
class Solution {
public:
    int numTilings(int N) {
        int mod = 1000000007;
        int dp[N+1][2];
        dp[0][1] = 1, dp[0][0] = 0;
        dp[1][1] = 1, dp[1][0] = 0;

        for(int i=2; i<N+1; i++){
            dp[i][1] = ((dp[i-1][1] + dp[i-2][1])%mod + (dp[i-1][0])%mod)%mod;
            dp[i][0] = ((dp[i-2][1]*2)%mod + (dp[i-1][0])%mod)%mod;
        }
        return dp[N][1];
    }
};
