# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
The question itself is pretty weird if you look at the way it is described but pretty simple once you try to plot a picture in your head. Now if you draw all the possibilites for first few test cases, you'll notice something.

`n = 1, ans = 1`
`n = 2, ans = 2`
`n = 3, ans = 5`
`n = 4, ans = 11`
`n = 5, ans = 24`
`n = 6, ans = 53`
`n = 7, ans = 117`

From the 4th testcase onwards, it follows a pattern which can be formulated as:
`ans[i] = 2 * ans[i - 1] + ans[i - 3]`

And that is it.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Create an array of size `n` and do a tabulated fibbonaci. Define for first 3 base cases i.e., `n = 1, 2, 3` and calculate for the rest.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(n)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: O(n)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public int numTilings(int n) {
        if(n == 1) return 1;
        if(n == 2) return 2;
        if(n == 3) return 5;
        int mod = 1000000007;
        int[] ans = new int[n];
        ans[0] = 1;
        ans[1] = 2;
        ans[2] = 5;
        for(int i = 3; i < n; i++) {
            ans[i] = (((ans[i - 1] % mod) * 2)% mod + ans[i - 3] % mod) % mod;
        }
        return ans[n - 1]; 
    }
}
```

