# Approach

Matrix Exponentiation is one of the most interesting techniques in competitive programming where you can reduce the complexity of your solution from O(N) to O(Log N) for a lot of recurrence relations.

I'll not be going into the details of the recurrence relation. This post is about understanding matrix exponentiation given some recurrence relation which in our case is: 

F(N) = 2\*F(N-1) + 1\*F(N-3)

The above equation can be rewritten as:

F(N) = 2\*F(N-1) + 0\*F(N-2) + 1\*F(N-3)

So the current value is depending on 3 previous values

[1st Matrix] = [Some matrix] * [3rd Matrix]

![1.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/2a2fc543-bd81-4e4c-88cc-8bb12b75419a_1671863617.9997604.png)

Dimension of the 1st and 3rd matrix is 3\*1 so the dimension of the 2nd matrix must be 3\*3

According to our equation:

F(N) = 2\*F(N-1) + 0\*F(N-2) + F(N-3)
F(N-1) = F(N-1)
F(N-2) = F(N-2)

Writing this in matrix form we get our second matrix as:

| 2 0 1 |
| 1 0 0 |
| 0 1 0 |

Our relation becomes:

![2.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/7e518475-9018-4cd5-a491-26c60214b5e6_1671864145.4730778.png)

Initial values are F(0) = 1, F(1) = 1, F(2) = 2

For N = 3 

![3.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/7bc0b7f3-0603-4dc9-ac9b-5aad0e6b3e3a_1671864277.6640637.png)

For N = 4

![5.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/1adf94e6-c6de-40c9-9c65-ed89cab4cc87_1671864831.8639169.png)


So for some N 

![6.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/23edab65-0784-4b83-9d0e-8faa89c09af7_1671864958.975979.png)


Thus we can multiply the second matrix N-2 times and finally multiply it with the base matrix to get the answer for F(N)

This multiplication of the matrix can be done using fast exponentiation which will provide us the final matrix in O(Log N) time 

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(Log N)
- Space complexity: O(1)

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:

    typedef long long ll;
    const int mod=1e9+7;

    void multiply(vector<vector<ll>> &A, vector<vector<ll>> &B){
        vector<vector<ll>> temp(3, vector<ll>(3));
        for(int i=0; i<3; ++i){
            for(int j=0; j<3; ++j){
                for(int k=0; k<3; ++k){
                    (temp[i][j]+=(A[i][k]%mod * B[k][j]%mod)%mod)%mod;
                }
            }
        } 
        A=temp;
    }

    void power(vector<vector<ll>> &A, ll n){
        if(n==1) return;
        power(A, n/2);
        multiply(A, A);
        if(n%2){
            vector<vector<ll>> B={{2, 0, 1}, {1, 0, 0}, {0, 1, 0}};
            multiply(A, B);
        }
    }

    int numTilings(int n) {
        if(n<=2)return n;
        vector<vector<ll>> A={{2, 0, 1}, {1, 0, 0}, {0, 1, 0}};
        power(A, n-2);
        return (2*A[0][0]%mod + A[0][1]%mod + A[0][2]%mod)%mod;
    }
};
```

