✔️ **Solution (Dynamic Programming - Tabulation)**
**1-D DP**
Simple basic approach to these question comprises of three steps :

**Step 1:** (putting   ![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/1a819d99-9305-456d-985d-81fc4c12fa8c_1639162617.0363584.png)   at the end , this can be done in **dp[i-1]** ways ) .

**Step 2**: (putting     ![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/c17ad4a1-1f58-4c94-88af-e110f1abc266_1639162680.2571974.png)  at the end , this can be done in **dp[i-2]** ways ) .


**Step 3**: ( putting all those boxes formed by the combination of ![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/a9033da0-53e2-4e72-b124-11af378e6c75_1639162724.4785063.png)![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/59eaaab0-4f85-4b12-bfc0-f1b7c664d34b_1639162735.3517957.png)

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/d5edcfbe-1754-4e60-a241-a3830bf63c88_1639162748.0943146.png)  
, this can be done by all those combinations **greater than or equal to 3 till n** )

**For example** : dp[4] = dp[3] + dp[2] + dp[1]*2 + 2 (2 combination formed by n in step 3)  ; 

So , we can genelarise the code as ,

**C++**

```
class Solution {
public:
    int numTilings(int n) {
        long long int MOD = 1000000007 ;
        vector<int>dp(n+2,0);
        dp[0]=0;
        dp[1]=1;
        dp[2]=2;
        for(int i=3;i<=n;i++)
        {
            dp[i]=(dp[i-1]%MOD+dp[i-2]%MOD+2)%MOD;   
            for(int j=3;j<i;j++)
            {
                dp[i]=(dp[i]%MOD+(dp[i-j]*2)%MOD)%MOD;
            }
        }
        return dp[n];
    }
};
```
Time Complexity : O(N^2)
Space Complexity : O(N), required maintaining dp

