solutions.content:
* Here In this solution we just need to check all possibilities from the current postion to next position and assign the mask values based on the filled situations.
* It's not actually the bitmasking level problem but taken the mask variable to indicates the possible states using the numbers.
* We will use memoization for the avoiding repetitive recursion tasks.
* Lets Try to under stand the all possible states and their possibilities:
* Consider the 2*2 grid. **This dimenstion is taken because this is the minimum dimension required to consider the generated states by using two types of tiles.**

	![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/5de6ead3-10f5-4bde-b9ce-dcefe52f74d3_1639195755.7855394.png)




* At last we will return 1 if all boxes **filled in valid manner by verifying mask is 0 means state 1.**

**Below is the code implementation of the above approach:**
```
class Solution {
public:

    const int mod = 1e9 + 7;
    int dp[1001][4];
    int n;
    int solve(int index,int mask)
    {
        if(index > n)
        {
            return 0;
        }
        if(index == n)
        {
            return mask == 0;
        }
        if(dp[index][mask] != -1) return dp[index][mask];

        int ans = 0;

        if(mask == 0)
        {
            ans = (ans + solve(index+1,0))%mod;
            ans = (ans + solve(index+2,0))%mod;
            ans = (ans + solve(index+1,1))%mod;
            ans = (ans + solve(index+1,2))%mod;


        }
        else if(mask == 1)
        {
            ans = (ans + solve(index+1,3))%mod;
            ans = (ans + solve(index+1,2))%mod;
        }
        else if(mask == 2)
        {
            ans = (ans + solve(index+1,3))%mod;
            ans = (ans + solve(index+1,1))%mod;
        }
        else
        {
            ans = solve(index+1,0) % mod;
        }
        return dp[index][mask] = ans;
    }

    int numTilings(int N) {
        n = N;
        memset(dp,-1,sizeof dp);

        return solve(0,0);

    }
};
```

