It's clear that DP is the best way to solve it. However, many solutions seem to have lengthy math drivation before deriving the transfer equation.

If we define two tilting problems, the logic seems a lot simpler:
* Let `a[n]` be the tiling ways for `2*n` board (i.e., the answer)
* Let `b[n]` be the tiling ways for `2*n+1` board (i.e., the helper DP array)

We have transfer equations:
```cpp
a[n] = a[n-1] + a[n-2] + 2*b[n-2];
b[n] = a[n-1] + b[n-1];
```
with initial conditions:
```cpp
a[0] = 1, a[1] = 1, b[0] = 0, b[1] = 1;
```

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/zzg_zzm/image_1569793400.png)

```cpp
    int numTilings(int n) {
      if (n == 1) return 1;

      // initial values
      long a, a_pre1 = 1, a_pre2 = 1; // 2xn solution
      long b, b_pre1 = 1, b_pre2 = 0; // 2xn+1 solution
      const long mod = 1000000007;      

      while (--n >= 1) // iterate n-1 times
      { 
        a = (a_pre1 + a_pre2 + 2*b_pre2)%mod;
        b = (a_pre1 + b_pre1)%mod;

        // update a and b
        a_pre2 = a_pre1;
        a_pre1 = a;

        b_pre2 = b_pre1;
        b_pre1 = b;
      }
      return a;
    }
```

