Whenever we are asked to find the number of ways we try to think from recursion point of view (Not everytime but mostly we get a way to proceed ahead)
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->

# Approach
![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/6b54c7a3-df31-4473-8199-81a4b93c2c81_1671903084.671635.png)
![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/95ec3884-a58f-4ace-b8c7-cd53732dcf1e_1671903222.124374.png)

Thus we get two recurrence relations
f(n) = f(n-1) + f(n-2) + 2*(n-2)
g(n) = f(n-1) + g(n-1)

# Recursion - TLE

-> instead of taking a seperate function call for g(n), I have written g(n) = f(n, true)
```
class Solution {
public:
    int m = 1e9 + 7;
    long long f(int n, bool flag){
        if (n < 3) return n;
        if (flag)
            return (f(n-1, false) + f(n-1, true)) % m;
        return (f(n-1, false) + f(n-2, false) + 2*f(n-2, true)) % m;
    }
    int numTilings(int n) {
        int ans = f(n, false);
        return ans;
    }
};
```

# Memorization 
-> dp[1001][2] is created as n can take a maximum of 1000
-> repeated calls are pruned
```
class Solution {
public:
    int m = 1e9 + 7;
    long long f(int n, bool flag, vector<vector<int>> &dp){
        if (n < 3) return n;
        if (dp[n][flag] != -1) return dp[n][flag];
        if (flag)
            return dp[n][flag] = (f(n-1, false, dp) + f(n-1, true, dp)) % m;
        return dp[n][flag] = (f(n-1, false, dp) + f(n-2, false, dp) + 2*f(n-2, true, dp)) % m;
    }
    int numTilings(int n) {
        vector<vector<int>> dp(1001, vector<int>(2, -1));
        int ans = f(n, false, dp);
        return ans;
    }
};
```

# Tabular 
```
class Solution {
public:
    int m = 1e9 + 7;
    int numTilings(int n) {
        vector<long long> f(1001, 0);
        vector<long long> g(1001, 0);
        f[1] = g[1] = 1;
        f[2] = g[2] = 2;
        for(int i = 3;i <= n; i++){
            g[i] = (f[i-1] + g[i-1])%m ;
            f[i] = (f[i-1] + f[i-2] + 2*g[i-2])%m;
        }
        return f[n];
    }
};
```
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
    Recursion - O(3**n) for each state we are trying to explore 3 sub states
    Memorization and Tabular form - O(n)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity:
    O(n)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->


```

