# Intuition
At each possible length, try to check for different combinations at the right most end. For each such combination, count the number of  ways of filling the previous tiles (Dynamic Programming).

# Approach
`dp[i]` indictes the number of ways of filling a `2 * (i+1)` board.
Update each `dp[i]` by using the above logic.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: `O(n * n)`

- Space complexity: `O(n)`

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int numTilings(int n) {
        const int mod = 1e9 + 7;
        vector<long> dp(max(3, n), 0);
        dp[0] = 1; dp[1] = 2; dp[2] = 5;
        for(int i=3; i<n; i++) {
            //          |       --      |-   |
            //          |       --      |   -|
            dp[i] = (dp[i-1] + dp[i-2] + 2*dp[i-3]) % mod;
            long k = 1;
            for(int j=i-4; j>=0; --j) {
                //       |  --  --  --  |
                //       |-   --  --   -|
                k = (k + dp[j]) % mod;
            }
            dp[i] = (dp[i] + 2*k) % mod;

        }
        return dp[n-1];
    }
};
```

