solutions.content:
Let us form a 2-D table (i.e. simply an array) by the name dp such that it contains the no. of ways to tile a floor. The n'th element in the array denotes the no. of ways to tile 2xn floor. dp[n=N] will be the anwer.
Let us consider the a few tile configurations added to the right end.
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/08da9ec1-2710-4ae1-8a04-6131844c89a6_1657712108.71259.jpeg)
Thus the code for the following will be:
```
def numTilings(self, n: int) -> int:
	dp = [0] * (n+1)
	dp[0] = 1
	for i in range(1,n+1):
		for j in range(1,i+1):
			if j<=2:
				dp[i] += dp[i-j]
			else:
				dp[i] += dp[i-j]*2                
	return dp[n]%(10**9+7)
```
It's Dynamic Programming but a bit slow, actually a lot slow, on leetcode it beats only 5% of the solutions in time. Clearly, it is O(n^2). Can we optimize it to O(n)? Yes. Let's do some maths :)

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/7ca27c26-bffb-40c3-9353-661f0f780dc3_1657712258.206752.jpeg)

Wow, math saves our little pc a lot of unnecessary manual work, let's use it in our code now.
```
def numTilings(self, n: int) -> int:
	dp = [0] * (n+1)
	if n<=1:
		return 1
	elif n<=2:
		return 2
	elif n<=3:
		return 5
	dp[0] = 1
	dp[1] = 1
	dp[2] = 2
	dp[3] = 5

	for i in range(4,n+1):
		dp[i] = 2*dp[i-1] + dp[i-3]              
	return dp[n]%(10**9+7)
```
Now, its 0(n)! It beats 90% on leetcode. Great job!
