So what we essentially wanna do is put the tilings in such a way that whole area is covered. Now we have two types of tilings domino and tromino. Taking a high level view of the problem we get that at every step we have to make a choice whether to pick a domino or tromino and if a domino which orientation and if a tromino then which orientation. Sounds like recursion to me!

Let's start recursion then.

So let’s say we are at position x now we look into our options:
1.	Pick a domino: Here again we got two choices:
	a.	We take vertical domino. So when we take a vertical domino this whole column is covered and we can move to x-1.![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/c3f52349-593b-410d-b9c6-822304f3ca12_1639195839.8293874.png)
	b.	We take a horizontal domino. So when we take a horizontal domino two columns of a row are covered and the row other than this has only one option to place a horizontal domino, hence we can move to x-2.![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/8221f839-eb26-4e2d-a880-b9dabde93eb7_1639195865.765447.png)
2.	Pick a tromino: Now when we pick a tromino we will fill one column and fill the other one partially. Now in the partial filled column we have two options:![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/ca1ff0b7-56d7-4046-9b4e-2c04904a3777_1639195892.081208.png)
	a.	We can start a tromino from there. By doing this we would have filled 3 columns completely.![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/4c8465a6-1b8f-424c-a9c4-18edeb015278_1639195923.0817401.png)
b.	We can start a horizontal domino from the partially unfilled area.![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/7ef8b8cd-c16a-4b23-9664-291b5d1119ba_1639195945.061751.png)

So talking mathematically, 

f(x) = part1 + part2 + part3 where, 
part1 = f(x-1) => the case of vertical domino 
part2 = f(x-2) => the case of horizontal domino 
part3 = 2*p(x-1) => the case for tromino 

Now we know f(x), let’s define p(x). 

p(x) is for the partially filled column. So whenever we put a tromino we call p(x-1) where tromino is put at x so the column previous to that would be partially filled right. Now, 

p(x) = part4 + part5 
part4 = f(x-2) => case where we put another domino and completely fill the columns 
part5 = p(x-1) => case where we put horizontal domino in the partially unfilled column, thus creating another partially filled column. 

Now you might think why I multiplied by 2 in part3. The reason is that we can place a tromino in 2 ways either its ‘L’ shaped or mirror image of ‘L’. Hence multiplication by 2.

Recursive Code:

```
class Solution {
    int mod = (int)Math.pow(10,9)+7;
    public int numTilings(int n) {
        return (int)(recur( n ) % mod);
    }
    public long recur ( int x ) {
        if ( x==0 ) {
            return 1;
        }
        if ( x<0 ) {
            return 0;
        }
        return (long)2*partial(x-1) + recur(x-2) + recur(x-1);
    }
    public long partial( int x ) {
        if ( x==0 ) {
            return 0;
        }
        if ( x<3 ) {
            return x-1;
        }
        return (long)partial(x-1) + recur(x-2);
    }
}
```

Now recursion leads to TLE. What to we do know?
Answer: Memoization

```
class Solution {
    int mod = (int)Math.pow(10,9)+7;
    Long[] full;
    Long[] part;
    public int numTilings(int n) {
        full = new Long[n+1];
        part = new Long[n+1];
        return recur( n );
    }
    public int recur ( int x ) {
        if ( x==0 ) {
            return 1;
        }
        if ( x<0 ) {
            return 0;
        }
        int temp = 0;
        if ( full[x]!=null ) {
            temp = (int)(full[x]%mod);
            return temp;
        }
        full[x] = (long)2*partial(x-1) + recur(x-2) + recur(x-1);
        temp = (int)(full[x]%mod);
        return temp;
    }
    public int partial( int x ) {
        if ( x==0 ) {
            return 0;
        }
        if ( x<3 ) {
            return x-1;
        }
        int temp = 0;
        if ( part[x]!=null ) {
            temp = (int)(part[x]%mod);
            return temp;
        }
        part[x] = (long)partial(x-1) + recur(x-2);
        temp = (int)(part[x]%mod);
        return temp;
    }
}
```

