The idea is very simple, almost every linear recurrence relation can be calculated in O(log n) time and O(1) space. This relies on a process called fast matrix exponentiation.
There are many posts that explain the reasoning behind the recurrence relation. This post will not go into that. It will take the recurrence relation and implement it in O(log n) time complexity.
With that out of the way, let f(N) represent the number of ways to tile a 2xN matrix. The recurrence relation is
f(n) = 2 * f(n-1) + f(n-3)
Now label the following matrix as A:
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/1a4d8870-9083-4b51-a04b-62e3ee5ed34d_1594640964.948474.png)
and label the following matrix as B(n):
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/15816a38-847c-4a8c-a656-f9e660581944_1594636909.6774485.png)
What is the product of A and B(n-1)? It is shown below.
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/1988c7ee-5a2e-4efb-81f9-d0d063d997ed_1594637598.9115956.png)
This product, from the recurrence relation, is clearly B(n).
Thus, from our original recurrence, we have found a new recurrence relation:
B(n) = A * B(n-1).
What is the base case for this recurrence? Define B(2) as 
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/a32c9faf-c902-4225-bf33-ef77eec40d17_1594640490.3104377.png)
Now, from the recurrence,
B(3) = A * B(2)
B(4) = A * B(3) = A * A * B(2) = A^2 * B(2)
B(5) = A * B(4) = A^3 * B(2)
From this pattern,
B(n) = A^(n-2) * B(2)
And how is A^(n-2) calculated? We return to the title of this post, fast matrix exponentiation.
The fact of the matter is that a constant time formula for this recurrence can also be derived. However, as in the formula for the Fibonacci sequence, it may contain irrational numbers, which cannot accurately be represented on computers. This post contains an O(log n) procedure for this exponentiation.
The process is very simple. If X is a matrix, then
X^n = X * X^(n-1)                      if n is odd
X^n = (X^2)^(n/2)                     if n is even
There are atmost two multiplications for each digit in the binary representation of n (which has log n digits). Thus, this algorithm takes O(log n) time.
**Code:**
```
class Solution {
public:
    int numTilings(int n) {
        if(n==1) return 1;
        else if(n==2) return 2;
        vector<vector<long long>> a{
            {2, 0, 1},
            {1, 0, 0},
            {0, 1, 0}
        }, res{
            {1, 0, 0},
            {0, 1, 0},
            {0, 0, 1}
        }, temp(3,vector<long long>(3));
        n-=2;
        while(n){
            if(n&1){
                for(int i=0;i<3;i++){
                    for(int j=0;j<3;j++){
                        temp[i][j]=0;
                        for(int k=0;k<3;k++){
                            temp[i][j]+=(res[i][k]*a[k][j])%1000000007;
                        }
                        temp[i][j]%=1000000007;
                    }
                }
                res=temp;
                n--;
            }
            if(n){
                for(int i=0;i<3;i++){
                    for(int j=0;j<3;j++){
                        temp[i][j]=0;
                        for(int k=0;k<3;k++){
                            temp[i][j]+=(a[i][k]*a[k][j])%1000000007;
                        }
                        temp[i][j]%=1000000007;
                    }
                }
                a=temp;
            }
            n>>=1;
        }
        return (2*res[0][0]+res[0][1]+res[0][2])%1000000007;
    }
};
```
Complexity: O(log n) time
					O(1) space (only three 3x3 matrices and one variable)

