# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
The solution is a recursive approach. The question asks us to take turns and use first $$X$$ stones that were not previously taken and add them to score. $$X$$ can be any number from $$1 \; to \;\; 2M$$ (M starts with 1). $$M$$ is updated in each step as  $$max(X,M)$$. 
We  can form a function with parameters $$i, m, a$$, where,
- $$i$$ is current index upto where we have used the stones (we would like to pick any $$X$$ stones beginning from $$i_{th}$$ stone).
- $$m$$ is current value of $$M$$.
- $$a$$ denotes whose turn is this, $$a = 1$$ means Alice turn $$a = 0$$ means Bob's turn.

# Approach
When it is turn of Alice we return the max possible answer by adding the values of first $$X $$index starting from $$ i \;\; to \;\; i+2m$$ as $$X$$ can range from $$(1 \; to \; 2m)$$ and update $$m$$ as max of $$m$$ and $$X$$ (remember $$X$$ is count of indices that we can pick up starting from $$i$$ not index itself).
When it is the turn of Bob, we do nothing but skip the indexes starting from $$i$$ (that we don't want to give to Alice), we take the minimum over all possible $$Xs$$ as Bob wants to minimize score of Alice.
Finally memoize the solution using a `dp` array.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
$$O(n^3)
$$
# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int dp[101][301][2];
    int solve(int i , int n , int m , vector<int>& v, int a){
        if(i>=n){
            return 0;
        }
        if(dp[i][m][a]!=-1) return dp[i][m][a];
        int ans = 0;
        int cur =0;
        \\ alice turn
        if(a){
            for(int j = i;j<n&&j<i+2*m;j++){
                cur+=v[j];
                ans = max(ans,cur+solve(j+1,n,max(m,j-i+1),v, 1-a));
            }
        }
        \\ bob turn
        else{
            ans = 1e6;
            for(int j = i;j<n&&j<i+2*m;j++){
                ans = min(ans,solve(j+1,n,max(m,j-i+1),v, 1-a));
            }
        }
        return dp[i][m][a]=ans;
    }
    int stoneGameII(vector<int>& piles) {
        int n = piles.size();
        memset(dp,-1,sizeof(dp));
        return solve(0,n,1,piles,1);
    }
};
```

