# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
The intuition behind the solution is to use dynamic programming with memoization to determine the maximum number of stones Alice can get. The approach involves recursively exploring all possible moves and keeping track of the maximum stones obtained.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
1. Initialize the prefix sum array prefixSum to store the sum of stones from each index to the end of the array.
1. Initialize a memoization array memo to store the results of subproblems. The value -1 indicates that the result has not been calculated yet.
1. Call the dfs function, which is a recursive helper function that performs the dynamic programming with memoization.
1. In the dfs function, handle the base cases:
- If we have reached the end of the array (i == piles.length), return 0.
- If 2 * M is greater than or equal to the remaining number of piles, return the sum of stones from the current index to the end of the array (prefixSum[i]).
- If the result for the current subproblem has already been calculated, return the memoized result.
5. Initialize the maxStones variable to store the maximum number of stones Alice can get from the current position.
6. Iterate from 1 to 2 * M (inclusive) to try different numbers of piles that Alice can take.
- For each iteration, calculate the remaining stones by subtracting the result of the recursive call with the updated index and the new maximum number of piles (Math.max(M, x)).
- Update maxStones with the maximum value between the current maxStones and the remaining stones.
7. Memoize the result by storing it in the memo array and return maxStones.
8. The main stoneGameII function initializes the prefix sum array, the memoization array, and starts the recursion by calling dfs with the initial parameters.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
The time complexity of this solution is O(n^2) because the recursion has two nested loops: one iterating from 1 to 2 * M, and the other iterating from the current index to the end of the array.

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
 The space complexity is O(n^2) as well due to the memoization array.

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public int stoneGameII(int[] piles) {
        int n = piles.length;
        int[] prefixSum = new int[n];
        prefixSum[n - 1] = piles[n - 1];

        for (int i = n - 2; i >= 0; i--) {
            prefixSum[i] = prefixSum[i + 1] + piles[i];
        }

        int[][] memo = new int[n][n];
        for (int[] row : memo) {
            Arrays.fill(row, -1);
        }

        return dfs(piles, prefixSum, memo, 0, 1);
    }
     private int dfs(int[] piles, int[] prefixSum, int[][] memo, int i, int M) {
        if (i == piles.length) {
            return 0;
        }

        if (2 * M >= piles.length - i) {
            return prefixSum[i];
        }

        if (memo[i][M] != -1) {
            return memo[i][M];
        }

        int maxStones = 0;
        for (int x = 1; x <= 2 * M; x++) {
            int remainingStones = prefixSum[i] - dfs(piles, prefixSum, memo, i + x, Math.max(M, x));
            maxStones = Math.max(maxStones, remainingStones);
        }

        memo[i][M] = maxStones;
        return maxStones;
    }
}
```

