solutions.content:
This memoization solution is very straightforward. The reason why I avoid Dynamic Programming is its base cases are a little bit arkward. The prefix sum array is constructed for the purpose of fast calculation of range sum. 
```
pfxSum[0] = 0
pfxSum[1] = 0 + piles[0]
       ...
pfxSum[i] = 0 + piles[0] + ... + piles[i-1]
pfxSum[i+1] = 0 + piles[0] + ... + piles[i-1] + piles[i]

//Thus piles[i : j] = pfxSum[j+1] - pfxSum[i];
```

Now there's really no tricks in this Solution.

```
class Solution {
    private int[] pfxSum;
    private int n;

    // memo[i][j] : max score when starting with stone index = i, with M = j
    private int[][] memo;

    public int stoneGameII(int[] piles) {
        this.n = piles.length;
        this.memo = new int[n][n+1];

        this.pfxSum = new int[n+1];
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            pfxSum[i+1] = pfxSum[i] + piles[i]; 
        }

        return dfs(0, 1);
    }

    private int dfs(int idx, int M) {
        if (idx >= n) return 0;
        if (memo[idx][M] != 0) return memo[idx][M];

        int res = 0;

        // may take [0, 2 * M] piles 
        for (int i = idx; i < Math.min(idx + 2 * M, n); i++) {
            int X = i - idx + 1;

            // the other player will start from index = i+1, with M = max(M, X);
            res = Math.max(res, pfxSum[n] - pfxSum[idx] - dfs(i + 1, Math.max(M, X)));
        }

        return memo[idx][M] = res;
    }
}
```

