solutions.content:
Here, memo[i][m] represents maximum number of stones Alice can pick from position i till end where m governs total no of stones she can pick, i.e. x, such that 1 <= x <= 2 * m
When at position i, if Alice can pick max stone_count stones, then Bob can pick suffixSum[i] - stone_count stones. 
So for our dp state (i, m)
memo[i][m] = Max no of stones Alice can pick
suffixSum[i] - memo[i][m] = Max no of stones Bob can pick

Let's say we are at position i now, and m = 2, then Alice can pick piles x: 1, 2, 3... 4
then for Bob, in next position, he can get stones memo[i + x][max(x, m)], which means Alice can get stones suffixSum[i + x] - memo[i + x][max(x, m)]

So, here we want to maximize stones Alice can get
suffix[i] - suffix[i + x] + suffix[i + x] - memo[i + x][max(x, m)]
= suffix[i] - memo[i + x][max(x, m)]
, where x = 1... 2 * m

Also here m represents limit on no of piles to be chosen, so it cant exceed no of piles.
Top-down approach
```
class Solution {
public:
    int stoneGameII(vector<int>& piles) {
        int n = piles.size();        
        vector<vector<int>> memo(n, vector<int>(n, -1));
        vector<int> suffix(n + 1, 0);
        for (int i = n - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
            suffix[i] = suffix[i + 1] + piles[i];
        }

        return getStones(piles, 0, 1, memo, suffix);
    }

    int getStones(vector<int>& piles, int index, int m, vector<vector<int>>& memo, vector<int>& suffix) {     
        if (index + 2 * m >= piles.size()) {
            return suffix[index];
        } 

        if (memo[index][m] != -1) {
            return memo[index][m];
        }

        int val = -1;
        for (int x = index + 1; x <= index + 2 * m; x++) {
            val = max(val, suffix[index] - getStones(piles, x, max(x - index, m), memo, suffix));    
        }

        memo[index][m] = val;
        return val;
    }
};
```

