solutions.content:
When it is Alice's turn, she wants to pick the option that maximizes her score, and when it is Bob's turn, he wants to pick the option that minimizes Alice's score. 

The question asks us to find the maximum score that Alice can have, which means we have to return the `(sum of array + maximum score) / 2` . This is because, say, `A` and `B` stands for Alice's score and Bob's score respectively. Our approach will give us the maximum possible `A-B`, and the sum of the array is `A+B` . Hence, we have:  `(A-B) + (A+B) = 2A`. 

```
class Solution {
    public int stoneGameII(int[] piles) {
        int sum = Arrays.stream(piles).sum();
        int[][][] dp = new int[piles.length][piles.length + 1][2];
        getMax(piles, 0, 1, dp, 0);

        return (sum + dp[0][1][0]) / 2;
    }

    private int getMax(int[] p, int start, int M, int[][][] dp, int myTurn){
        if (start >= p.length) return 0;
        if (dp[start][M][myTurn] != 0) return dp[start][M][myTurn];

        int max = Integer.MIN_VALUE;
        int min = Integer.MAX_VALUE;
        for (int i = start; i < Math.min(start + 2 * M, p.length); i++){
            int x = getMax(p, i + 1, Math.max(M, i - start + 1), dp, Math.abs(myTurn - 1));
            int sum = 0;
            for (int j = start; j <= i; j++) sum += p[j];
            if (myTurn == 0) max = Math.max(sum + x, max);
            else min = Math.min(-sum + x, min);
        }

        dp[start][M][myTurn] = myTurn == 0? max : min;
        return dp[start][M][myTurn];
    }
}
```

